# mcp-server scope 0 — reject non-POST methods with 405.
#
# The MCP Streamable-HTTP transport uses two channels at the same
# endpoint:
#   POST /mcp  — client→server JSON-RPC requests (what we handle)
#   GET  /mcp  — client opens a long-lived SSE stream for
#                server-INITIATED messages (notifications, sampling
#                requests, etc.)
#
# We don't offer the server→client SSE stream. The spec says a
# server that doesn't MUST return 405 Method Not Allowed for the
# GET so the client knows not to keep reopening it. Without this,
# Claude Code (and other Streamable-HTTP clients) loop: they
# reopen GET /mcp continuously, each time getting a confusing
# 200 + JSON-RPC error from the fall-through path instead of a
# clean rejection.
#
# `@halt = true` stops the pipeline here so parse@0 / dispatch@100
# / respond@200 never run for the GET. Body is explicit (not
# envelope projection) for the same dev-mode-leak reason as
# respond.txcl. The `Allow: POST` header is the conventional
# companion to a 405.
#
# DELETE /mcp (session teardown in the spec) also lands here and
# gets a 405 — fine, since we run stateless sessions with nothing
# to tear down.
WHEN @src == "http" && @web.req.method != "POST"
  EMIT @web.res.status = 405,
       @web.res.body = b64"Method Not Allowed: this MCP endpoint accepts POST only.\n",
       @web.res.headers.allow.0 = "POST",
       @web.res.headers.content-type.0 = "text/plain; charset=utf-8",
       @halt = true
